And my deliverables are not  like tenure track ish, but the closeness of the culture means I make immediate impact - good or bad.
For my institute, for my colleagues, for my students most importantly. There's nothing noble about this. It is work. Exhausting work.
But I can't begin to tell you guys how many somethings I have to make out of negative nothing on a daily to make stuff happen here.
When I left the US to come back home, that was a career move as much as a personal one. I didn't leave academia. I moved.
We have so much work to do. And I'm getting tired. Already. We need more us-es! #caribbeanDH cc: @elotroalex

1) Culturally, internet is still regarded as a luxury. 
2) I spend more time teaching that we have Cbean issues/topics worth researching.
This is my 3rd semester teaching the 1st DH undergrad course in the anglo-Cbean (that I know of). Learned a couple things...
Well, it's the same convo really. Except means two diff. things in R1 school vs. small Cbean island 12-yo institution. Just saying...
We need more stuff. Stuff is expensive. We need more funds. People don't get what we're doing. They won't give us funds. We can't get stuff.
Not that we don't have nice things. No shade or pity party here. But I find  #pocoDH #caribbeanDH convos missing a critical/practical piece.
Challenges facing small insititutions in developing countries really have very little to do w/ the fancy things we get to talk about all day
These are the types of conversations that metro #dh folk who really care about open access to learning need to be talking about.
Except the internet doesn't work, though.
